                        <div class=col-lg-6 data-aos=fade-right>
                            <p class="mb-4 mb-lg-6"><b>DISCIPLINA</b><br>
                            Far Eastern Creative Association of
                            musicians, DJs and artists.
                            The main goal of the project is to shed light on electronic music,
                            technology and art by organizing
                            relevant events in the Far East of Russia.
                            In 2016, our team, together with the Goethe Institute,
                            became the organizer of Sound Art Unsound x CTM Dislocation.
                            In 2017, in the summer, on the roof of the Marine Station, we held a major joint event with the TRIP label starring of Nina Kravitz.
                            In autumn, the guests of our event were residents of the Kiev club "Closer" and the Berlin "Club der Visionaere"
                            In 2018-2019, a resident spoke at our events
                            German label Giegling - Ateq.
                            As well as residents of reputable domestic formations
                            Arma17 and Roots United.

                            Today, Vladivostok can be safely called
                            the most progressive city in the eastern part of Russia.In October 2020, we, together with the Goethe Institute, are organizing a festival whose main goal
                            is the popularization of electronic music and media art.
                            By combining the creative potential of the Far East, Europe and Asia,
                            we will get a fundamentally new cultural connection.
                            </p>
                        </div>
                        <div class=col-lg-6 data-aos=fade-left>
                            <p><b>Valentin Tszin</b><br> is a Russian-born artist and dance researcher based in Berlin. His method (named 4/4 4/3 4/0) draws on the forms and fundamental principles of dramatic theatre, taekwondo, butoh and throat singing.
                            Tszin's body of work varies greatly in scale; he works across a contrasting range of formats, from ascetic solos to intricate group concepts. His projects have been presented to diverse audiences internationally, some having involved up to one hundred people.
                            Interdisciplinary dialogue in the arts is the way forward, according to Tszin. Beyond just dance, he has been commissioned to produce works for a wide variety of contexts; he has been involved in the worlds of architecture (he created a piece to inaugurate a building designed by Zaha Hadid), film (he has had a career in cinema spanning over a decade), contemporary art, theatre, and new media. Through this unique hybridized approach, he attempts to push the boundaries of the body and mind, whether his own, his dancers' or his audience's.

                            He has been producing his most recent works in collaboration with various techno musicians.
                            Valentin Tszin regularly conducts international master classes to explore with his students the process of collective creation. The idea that one's perceptions of reality are malleable through the alteration of one's physical body and state of mind is one that is axial to his method, and one that he furthermore believes is capable of changing the way people create art and interact with the world on a larger scale.
                            </p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <div class=row>
                        <div class=col-lg-6 data-aos=fade-right>
                            <p class="mb-4 mb-lg-6"><b>ILYA BOORDIN</b><br>
                            Russian media artist, musician, producer.
                            Currently based in Vladivostok. For 14 years he has been developing and popularizing electronic music and visual art in the Far East of Russia. Founder of the CON and Discipline projects (Vladivostok)
                            Since 2018, Ilya has been actively collaborating with German artists Valentin Jing, X TIN, Daniel Williams and Stanislav Glazov as part of the EXPRESSION project, an annual audio-visual performance that combines electronic music, choreography and visual art.
                            Since the fall of 2019, Ilya and Valentin's joint project “Music - Art - Discipline”, an audio-visual performative festival via offline and online format, began to be prepared.
                            In April 2020, they are launching the BUTOH CHANNEL educational project dedicated to Japanese Butoh culture.
                            At the same time, amid a pandemic, Ilya launches an independent streaming channel Archive.stream, the purpose of which is to collect an archive of works by electronic musicians and DJs from the Russian Far East.
                            </p>
                        </div>
                        <div class=col-lg-6 data-aos=fade-left>
                            <p><b>PETER KIRN</b><br> Berlin-based journalist, curator, and composer/electronic artist Peter Kirn has a multi-faceted practice in creative technology that has made him a sought-after expert in how electronic expression can evolve. After a classical training in New York, where he studied composition with Tania León and co-founded the CUNY Graduate Center’s Contemporary Ensemble, he relocated in Berlin where he has expanded work in electronic media. Since 2013, he has produced the MusicMakers Hacklab as a program partner of CTM Festival, an international collaborative performance environment, which has expanded to collaborations with Nusasonic and Goethe-Institut Southeast Asia and MUTEK. He has also worked in collaborations with the European Space Agency, ARTYPICAL, SONAR+D, and TED, and has been a resource in creative technology including acting as consultant  to Rockstar Games, Native Instruments, and The New York Times, among others. In 2020, he is a co-host of AI labs with ARTYPICAL at MUTEK Montreal and TransArt [IT], the Space Art Sound Lab with ARTYPICAL and the Museum of Cosmonautics in Moscow, and co-curated SPACE.ZERO in Kaliningrad with support from the British Embassy in Moscow. He co-creates the MeeBlip hardware synthesizer. He has released music on Detroit Underground, Wunderblock Records, Kotä, Instruments of Discipline, Snork Enterprises, and his own Establishment.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
